# Cursor IDE Rules for UC7.5

## Repository Overview

This is the UC7.5 repository. This file provides guidelines and context to help Cursor AI understand the project structure, coding standards, and best practices.

## Project Structure

- `crown.html` - Main visualization file with embedded SVG crown graphic
- `README.md` - Project documentation
- `.github/copilot-instructions.md` - GitHub Copilot configuration

## Testing and Validation

### Testing Requirements
- Write tests for new features and bug fixes
- Ensure all tests pass before submitting changes
- Aim for meaningful test coverage

### Code Review
- All changes should be reviewed before merging
- Address feedback constructively
- Ensure changes don't break existing functionality

## Coding Standards

### General Principles
- Write clean, readable, and maintainable code
- Follow the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused on a single responsibility
- Add comments only when necessary to explain complex logic

### HTML/CSS/JavaScript Style
- Use consistent indentation with 4 spaces
- Use semantic HTML5 elements
- Keep styles organized and well-commented
- Follow modern web standards
- Ensure cross-browser compatibility

## Development Guidelines

### Code Quality
- Ensure all HTML is valid and well-formed
- Use modern CSS features appropriately
- Test in multiple browsers when making changes
- Optimize for performance and accessibility

### Documentation
- Keep README.md up to date with project information
- Document any new features or significant changes
- Include usage examples where helpful

## Git Workflow

- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Keep commits focused on a single change or feature
- Reference issue numbers in commits when applicable

## Security Best Practices

- Never commit secrets, API keys, or sensitive credentials
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Follow web security best practices
- Be mindful of XSS and other common vulnerabilities

## Additional Guidelines

- Be mindful of dependencies - keep the project lightweight
- Consider backwards compatibility when making changes
- Optimize for readability first, performance second
- When in doubt, ask for clarification or guidance

---

**Note:** This project is intentionally minimal. Maintain simplicity while adding new features.
